{"term":"2010","caseName":"Sossamon v. Texas","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/2010/08-1438","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - November 02, 2010","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/oral_argument_audio/21421","transcript":[{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We will hear argument in 08-1438, Sossamon v. Texas.","start":0,"stop":5.452,"duration":5.45},{"text":"You don't look like Mr. Schnapper.","start":5.452,"stop":7.07,"duration":1.62},{"text":"Mr. Russell.","start":7.07,"stop":7.654,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court: By accepting Federal funds for its prisons, Texas consented to suit for appropriate relief for violations of the Religious Land Use and Institutionalized Persons Act.","start":7.654,"stop":18.795,"duration":11.14},{"text":"The question in this case is whether that appropriate relief encompasses damages.","start":18.795,"stop":22.912,"duration":4.12},{"text":"If you simply asked what kind of relief is generally appropriate against a State, the answer would be no relief, not even an injunction, because States ordinarily are not subject even to suit without their consent.","start":22.912,"stop":33.368,"duration":10.46},{"text":"And so RLUIPA necessarily asks a more precise question, and that is what relief is appropriate against a State that has consented to be sued for violations of this sort.","start":33.368,"stop":43.16,"duration":9.79},{"text":"Damages, for example, are perfectly appropriate against a State that has consented to be sued for breach of contract.","start":43.16,"stop":49.247,"duration":6.09}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, what would it be, Mr. Russell, if there were a suit under RFRA because a Federal penal institution was not allowing for the religious practices that the act protects?","start":49.247,"stop":69.56,"duration":20.31}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"In--","start":69.56,"stop":72.179,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"In a suit under RFRA, could there be -- would damages be an appropriate remedy?","start":72.179,"stop":79.849,"duration":7.67}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"--In our view they are, although it's a different context, and we recognize that the government disagrees with us on that.","start":79.849,"stop":85.836,"duration":5.99},{"text":"We can't point to the Spending Clause-contract analogy that applies with respect to Spending Clause legislation as RFRA applies to the Federal Government.","start":85.836,"stop":95.358,"duration":9.52},{"text":"But there are other indications, including for example the long tradition of damages being appropriate relief for the violation of civil rights.","start":95.358,"stop":101.945,"duration":6.59}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, could we back up.","start":101.945,"stop":102.445,"duration":0.5},{"text":"You are saying you could get them against the Federal Government too, but the government doesn't think so?","start":102.445,"stop":109.249,"duration":6.8}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"That is our view, although we recognize that RLUIPA is different in this respect, in that it's a Spending Clause statute under which -- and this Court's decision in Barnes v. Gorman makes clear that damages are traditionally appropriate relief for the violation of any Spending Clause statute.","start":109.249,"stop":125.727,"duration":16.48},{"text":"Of course, there is also a tradition that damages are for the violation of civil rights.","start":125.727,"stop":129.945,"duration":4.22},{"text":"Take statutes like Title VI, Title VII, Title IX, section 504 of the ADA, the list goes on and on, where Congress has created damages as the quintessential remedy to enforce civil rights, and when Congress has subjected States to suits under such statutes, it has always put them on equal footing with other defendants and subjected them to damages as well.","start":129.945,"stop":150.092,"duration":20.15},{"text":"But even beyond that--","start":150.092,"stop":152.708,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"But did it use such language as \"appropriate relief\"?","start":152.708,"stop":155.56,"duration":2.85}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, for example--","start":155.56,"stop":156.246,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean, that's the question.","start":156.246,"stop":157.146,"duration":0.9},{"text":"Our cases say it has to be clear to the State when they go into one of these schemes, it has to be clear what liability they are subjecting themselves to.","start":157.146,"stop":167.202,"duration":10.06},{"text":"And in these other cases I think it was clear.","start":167.202,"stop":169.804,"duration":2.6},{"text":"I don't think it's clear with simply the word \"appropriate relief\".","start":169.804,"stop":173.338,"duration":3.53}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, we are not saying that the word \"appropriate relief\" in itself supplies the clarity.","start":173.338,"stop":177.807,"duration":4.47},{"text":"It's looking at that language and the way the court interprets statutes generally, among other things, looking at the tradition of what constitutes appropriate relief for a violation of this sort.","start":177.807,"stop":187.079,"duration":9.27},{"text":"We do think that Barnes v. Gorman is appropriate precedent in telling the court -- in telling Texas what kind of relief is generally thought appropriate to satisfy Congress's desire to remedy violations of a Spending Clause statute.","start":187.079,"stop":202.156,"duration":15.08},{"text":"We recognize, of course, that Barnes didn't involve sovereign defendants, but the local governments in that case had the same rights as a State would.","start":202.156,"stop":209.762,"duration":7.61},{"text":"It just comes out of the Spending Clause rather than the Eleventh Amendment.","start":209.762,"stop":213.214,"duration":3.45},{"text":"That is, both constitutional provisions prohibit Congress from subjecting defendants to damages suits under Spending Clause legislation without their consent.","start":213.214,"stop":222.502,"duration":9.29},{"text":"And this Court has enforced that identical constitutional right with the same clear statement test derived from Pennhurst v. Halderman.","start":222.502,"stop":229.723,"duration":7.22},{"text":"Even more, the contract analogy the Court relied on in Barnes is no less apt simply because one of the recipients is a State.","start":229.723,"stop":237.679,"duration":7.96}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The contract analogy, I suppose, would provide that the meaning of the contract is interpreted against the drafter.","start":237.679,"stop":245.851,"duration":8.17},{"text":"Right?","start":245.851,"stop":247.818,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"That would have been true in Barnes as well.","start":247.818,"stop":249.887,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":249.887,"stop":250.403,"duration":0.52},{"text":"So to the extent the State is arguing for a restrictive interpretation, it gets at least a little help from the fact that the Federal Government wrote the statute.","start":250.403,"stop":259.092,"duration":8.69}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it gets the same amount of help that the local governments got in Barnes, which wasn't enough.","start":259.092,"stop":263.312,"duration":4.22},{"text":"And Not only does the analogy, I think, apply; so does the remedy.","start":263.312,"stop":268.114,"duration":4.8},{"text":"Damages are a quintessential appropriate remedy for breach of contract by a State so long as the State has agreed to be sued for violation of a contract.","start":268.114,"stop":276.47,"duration":8.36}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Russell, the State looks at this statute and says, oh, this statute preserves the PLRA, and under the PLRA there are no damages without having a physical injury.","start":276.47,"stop":302.687,"duration":26.22},{"text":"So putting the PLRA together with PLRA is telling us it's not appropriate relief when there is no physical injury.","start":302.687,"stop":315.412,"duration":12.72}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would say two things about that.","start":315.412,"stop":317.031,"duration":1.62},{"text":"One, keep in mind that the PLRA limitations only apply to incarcerated individuals.","start":317.031,"stop":320.983,"duration":3.95},{"text":"It doesn't apply to the people RLUIPA protects in State-run nursing homes or mental health facilities.","start":320.983,"stop":326.47,"duration":5.49},{"text":"So Congress wouldn't have been thinking that appropriate relief is defined in some sense by the scope of the PLRA.","start":326.47,"stop":332.874,"duration":6.4},{"text":"In addition, we think that the fact that Congress expressly said that the PLRA applies to limit the relief that's otherwise available under RLUIPA shows that Congress didn't think that the PLRA itself made the relief inappropriate.","start":332.874,"stop":348.049,"duration":15.17},{"text":"It's simply that there is some relief that is otherwise appropriate that will be limited in some circumstances by the PLRA.","start":348.049,"stop":353.953,"duration":5.9}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But in the prison setting, then, isn't it an academic question, because there are not going to be damages anyway?","start":353.953,"stop":360.523,"duration":6.57}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"No, that's not true, for a couple of reasons.","start":360.523,"stop":362.892,"duration":2.37},{"text":"One, there are many cases involving pecuniary damages.","start":362.892,"stop":365.558,"duration":2.67},{"text":"There is destruction of religious items that won't be subject to the PLRA limitation.","start":365.558,"stop":369.795,"duration":4.24},{"text":"There are -- there are cases that give rise to pecuniary claims.","start":369.795,"stop":374.247,"duration":4.45},{"text":"So there is destruction of a religious item, a Bible or something like that.","start":374.247,"stop":377.615,"duration":3.37},{"text":"There are also cases in which the violation will result in a physical injury.","start":377.615,"stop":382.167,"duration":4.55},{"text":"There are cases where people are deprived of food for long periods of time.","start":382.167,"stop":386.285,"duration":4.12},{"text":"There is a case where a prison refused to transport an inmate for medical treatment outside the facility because he wouldn't take off his yarmulke.","start":386.285,"stop":392.689,"duration":6.4},{"text":"Congress, I don't think would have thought that the PLRA limitations rendered a damages remedy unimportant.","start":392.689,"stop":400.593,"duration":7.9},{"text":"And at the very least--","start":400.593,"stop":401.628,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Does it include punitive damages?","start":401.628,"stop":402.794,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"--Excuse me?","start":402.794,"stop":403.744,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Does it include punitive damages?","start":403.744,"stop":405.913,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"The statute, I think, does not in light of Barnes, because Barnes said that you get traditional contract remedies and punitive damages are not a traditional contract remedy.","start":405.913,"stop":416.47,"duration":10.56},{"text":"Beyond that tradition, though, there's also textual cues in the statue itself.","start":416.47,"stop":422.005,"duration":5.53},{"text":"There are three of them that I would like to focus on.","start":422.005,"stop":424.291,"duration":2.29},{"text":"I'll list them and then discuss them.","start":424.291,"stop":425.791,"duration":1.5},{"text":"One is the definitions section, which lumps States in together with local governments in the definition of \"government\".","start":425.791,"stop":431.028,"duration":5.24},{"text":"The second is the Federal enforcement provision, which specifically allows suits by the United States, but only for the equitable and declaratory relief that the State says is the only thing that's available under appropriate relief.","start":431.028,"stop":442.503,"duration":11.47},{"text":"And finally is the fact that the statute separately already authorizes suits for injunctive relief against State officials, making the addition of suits against States effectively surplusage unless some other kind of relief is available against the State.","start":442.503,"stop":455.727,"duration":13.22},{"text":"Beginning with the definitions section, this Court recognized in the United States v. Nordic Village that where Congress, in the Bankruptcy Act, defined \"governmental unit\" to include both the United States and a State, that Congress was making clear, quote, that","start":455.727,"stop":470.67,"duration":14.94},{"text":"\"States and Federal sovereigns are to be treated the same for immunity purposes. \"","start":470.67,"stop":474.724,"duration":4.05},{"text":"I think the same lesson comes out of the fact that RLUIPA defines \"governments\" to include not only States, but local governments, and subjects all governments to the same cause of action for the same appropriate relief.","start":474.724,"stop":484.913,"duration":10.19},{"text":"Congress was expressing there as clear as it could that there was a definitional equivalence between States and local government.","start":484.913,"stop":492.602,"duration":7.69}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah, but -- but, I mean, that means either that the Federal Government -- that the State government is liable for damages just as municipalities are, or that municipalities are immune to suit for damages just as the States are.","start":492.602,"stop":509.128,"duration":16.53},{"text":"I mean, that -- you don't know which way that cuts, do you?","start":509.128,"stop":511.478,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I will point you to other provisions of the statute.","start":511.478,"stop":513.68,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, maybe let's talk about them, then.","start":513.68,"stop":515.698,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":515.698,"stop":516.082,"duration":0.38},{"text":"One is the fact that, as I mentioned before, the statute -- and I think the State agrees -- already allows suits for injunctive relief against State officials in their official capacity.","start":516.082,"stop":526.371,"duration":10.29},{"text":"The only thing that adding States as defendant would accomplish in light of that would simply be a change in the caption of the lawsuit, unless States are subject to some relief that State officials under Ex parte Young are not.","start":526.371,"stop":539.161,"duration":12.79}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, except this would be a violation of a statute, not a violation of a constitutional right.","start":539.161,"stop":544.499,"duration":5.34},{"text":"So under Ex parte Young they couldn't necessarily get an injunction.","start":544.499,"stop":552.086,"duration":7.59}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would set aside the question of whether Ex parte Young applies of its own force.","start":552.086,"stop":557.723,"duration":5.64},{"text":"I think by defining \"officials\" as a form of government and authorizing suits for appropriate relief against officials, I think everybody agrees that that authorizes suits against the officials for at least injunctive relief.","start":557.723,"stop":570.547,"duration":12.82},{"text":"And then the question is, well, what does it accomplish to also authorize suits against States?","start":570.547,"stop":574.582,"duration":4.03},{"text":"And I think the obvious answer is it authorizes a damages claim against the State.","start":574.582,"stop":580.403,"duration":5.82},{"text":"And even in light of Barnes, the State seems to acknowledge that damages are appropriate relief against local governments under this statute.","start":580.403,"stop":588.841,"duration":8.44}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I can conceive of a case where -- where the State's violation of RLUIPA consists of a State statute that simply deprives the individual of his rights under RLUIPA.","start":588.841,"stop":604.184,"duration":15.34},{"text":"What State official would you -- would you sue?","start":604.184,"stop":607.303,"duration":3.12},{"text":"It seems to me you couldn't sue the State legislature, so it would make sense to have an injunction against the State.","start":607.303,"stop":616.325,"duration":9.02}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it's common in that circumstance to sue the State attorney general for Ex parte Young relief, for example, if you have a constitutional claim against the statute, as may very well have happened in the California case, or the governor, I guess.","start":616.325,"stop":626.514,"duration":10.19},{"text":"So I don't think that naming -- having a State as a defendant is necessary for that purpose here.","start":626.514,"stop":634.786,"duration":8.27},{"text":"In addition, as I mentioned before, I think even the State acknowledges that damages are appropriate relief against local governments, but Congress made clear that when it intended the identity of a party to result in a dramatically different scope of relief, it did so expressly, and you can see that in the U.S. enforcement provision.","start":634.786,"stop":653.581,"duration":18.8},{"text":"There, Congress specially authorized suits by the United States and had its own remedial provision which provides only for declaratory and injunctive relief.","start":653.581,"stop":662.603,"duration":9.02},{"text":"And that shows both that Congress didn't expect courts to simply figure out that different kinds of defendants would be subject to different appropriate relief, but also--","start":662.603,"stop":671.458,"duration":8.86}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't it argued that a possible purpose of that was to make it clear that the Federal Government couldn't sue a State to recover money that had been given to it?","start":671.458,"stop":681.997,"duration":10.54}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, the fact -- I would say two things about that.","start":681.997,"stop":684.432,"duration":2.44},{"text":"One is Congress didn't limit that provision to suits against States.","start":684.432,"stop":689.384,"duration":4.95},{"text":"It's anybody who gets sued by the United States is limited to equitable injunctive relief.","start":689.384,"stop":693.002,"duration":3.62},{"text":"And that's, again, an example of Congress treating States the same as everybody else.","start":693.002,"stop":696.906,"duration":3.9},{"text":"Whether they are sued by the United States or sued by a private party, it is the same relief.","start":696.906,"stop":700.942,"duration":4.04},{"text":"It's the same remedial provision and we think that suggests the same relief.","start":700.942,"stop":704.477,"duration":3.53},{"text":"That provision also kind of -- the language of that provision, \"injunctive or declaratory relief\", stands in pretty stark contrast to the facially broader phrase \"appropriate relief\" in the general provision.","start":704.477,"stop":716.117,"duration":11.64},{"text":"In addition to RLUIPA itself, I think it's also worth pointing out that the State had independent notice under section 2000(d)(7) -- this is the Rehabilitation Act Amendments of 1986, where Congress made clear to Texas that it would be subject to suit for damages under any statute that -- under a section of any statute that prohibits discrimination by Federal funding recipients.","start":716.117,"stop":740.25,"duration":24.13},{"text":"And I think the question here boils down to whether RLUIPA is materially distinguishable from section 504, which is listed in section 2000(d)(7) as an example of a statute prohibiting discrimination.","start":740.25,"stop":753.576,"duration":13.33},{"text":"And if -- I think that means that the catch-all has to at least be broad enough to encompass section 504, and in our view, the two statutes are not distinguishable.","start":753.576,"stop":763.032,"duration":9.46},{"text":"Both prohibit both the kind of disparate treatment of similarly-situated individuals that the State acknowledges constitutes discrimination and requires accommodations in some circumstances.","start":763.032,"stop":774.34,"duration":11.31}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You addressed the -- the effect of the issue here on persons who are in State institutions other than penal institutions.","start":774.34,"stop":786.398,"duration":12.06},{"text":"What would be -- what's the effect of the issue here on land use restrictions?","start":786.398,"stop":791.599,"duration":5.2},{"text":"Are there many cases in which issues involving land use restrictions are -- are raised in litigation against the State as opposed to a municipality?","start":791.599,"stop":802.471,"duration":10.87}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"It's quite rare.","start":802.471,"stop":803.288,"duration":0.82},{"text":"I am aware of one pending case in Vermont where there is a challenge to a -- a State environmental regulation, but for the most part it isn't.","start":803.288,"stop":812.262,"duration":8.97},{"text":"But if this Court were to, you know, section -- the provision that we are talking about here applies to land use as well as to institutionalized persons, and one would ordinarily think that the statute would have the same meaning depending on context.","start":812.262,"stop":826.253,"duration":13.99},{"text":"I recognize that the State's basic argument is that the meaning changes depending on who the defendant is, and I suppose if you accept that it could also depend on -- on what provision is being applied.","start":826.253,"stop":837.192,"duration":10.94},{"text":"But that's not normally how statutes work.","start":837.192,"stop":839.875,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But the answer to Justice Alito's question is that in the land use area, zoning for example, those are mostly cases against municipalities or counties?","start":839.875,"stop":853.198,"duration":13.32}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":853.198,"stop":853.965,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Not against the State.","start":853.965,"stop":854.634,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":854.634,"stop":855.467,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"The government is going to tell us that the standard for waiver with respect to the Federal Government is different from the standard with respect to the State.","start":855.467,"stop":867.275,"duration":11.81},{"text":"Do you -- I think that's what they are going to tell us.","start":867.275,"stop":869.308,"duration":2.03},{"text":"Do you agree with that?","start":869.308,"stop":870.108,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":870.108,"stop":870.81,"duration":0.7},{"text":"I actually don't understand them to be making that argument, either.","start":870.81,"stop":873.179,"duration":2.37},{"text":"But I know for sure that that's not our position.","start":873.179,"stop":875.029,"duration":1.85},{"text":"And the Court's decision in Barnes I think, for example, is entirely consistent with the Court's recent decisions, including for example in Richlin, where it's made clear that when you are considering the scope of waiver of sovereign immunity, you engage in ordinary statutory interpretation and then the sovereign is respected.","start":875.029,"stop":894.823,"duration":19.79},{"text":"If at the end of that interpretation the statute remains unclear, you know, certainly the sovereign wins.","start":894.823,"stop":900.494,"duration":5.67},{"text":"But--","start":900.494,"stop":900.927,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"But it seems to me that the States are in need of special protection.","start":900.927,"stop":905.562,"duration":4.63},{"text":"With -- with the Congress, if it's a Federal immunity, the Congress can always -- always change its law.","start":905.562,"stop":912.901,"duration":7.34}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well--","start":912.901,"stop":913.735,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"That just can't happen with the State.","start":913.735,"stop":915.618,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"--I don't know that this Court's cases support the idea that -- that heightened clear statement rule for States versus the Federal Government.","start":915.618,"stop":923.355,"duration":7.74},{"text":"If anything, I think they suggest the opposite, but so long as the statute is clear.","start":923.355,"stop":927.426,"duration":4.07}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"It's the suggestion of the opposite that -- that I am trying -- I am trying to explore.","start":927.426,"stop":932.144,"duration":4.72},{"text":"You have your white light on.","start":932.144,"stop":933.912,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":933.912,"stop":934.679,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Russell.","start":934.679,"stop":936.547,"duration":1.87},{"text":"Ms. Harrington.","start":936.547,"stop":945.403,"duration":8.86}]},{"speakerName":"Sarah Harrington","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:","start":945.403,"stop":947.636,"duration":2.23},{"text":"The Respondent in this case agrees that when it accepts Federal funds for its correctional system it voluntarily waives its sovereign immunity to private suits in Federal court to enforce RLUIPA, and it is clear under this Court's decisions in cases such as Franklin and Barnes that that voluntary waiver encompasses a waiver to suits for money damages.","start":947.636,"stop":966.566,"duration":18.93}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose Congress passes a statute that creates a private right of action against both the Federal Government and against the States and in both instances authorizes all appropriate relief.","start":966.566,"stop":977.855,"duration":11.29},{"text":"Are damages available in the action against the Federal Government as well as the State government?","start":977.855,"stop":983.742,"duration":5.89}]},{"speakerName":"Sarah Harrington","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it would depend on the context to answer both questions.","start":983.742,"stop":988.145,"duration":4.4}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the State -- the State provision is a Spending Clause provision.","start":988.145,"stop":992.197,"duration":4.05}]},{"speakerName":"Sarah Harrington","textObjs":[{"text":"Then the answer would be yes as to the States.","start":992.197,"stop":993.966,"duration":1.77},{"text":"This Court has been clear in cases such as Franklin and Barnes that in the Spending Clause context, unless Congress indicates an intent to rebut the presumption somehow--","start":993.966,"stop":1002.989,"duration":9.02}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And what about the Federal Government?","start":1002.989,"stop":1004.289,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Sarah Harrington","textObjs":[{"text":"--In the Federal Government probably not, although this Court has looked to background principles in interpreting words such as \"appropriate\".","start":1004.289,"stop":1011.261,"duration":6.97}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What sense does that make?","start":1011.261,"stop":1012.677,"duration":1.42},{"text":"Other than -- I know you are representing a client and so special pleading for your client is -- is to be expected, but I find that very difficult to accept.","start":1012.677,"stop":1021.967,"duration":9.29},{"text":"If \"all appropriate relief\" includes damages as against the State that accepts Federal money, then you know, what's good for the State should be good for the Federal Government.","start":1021.967,"stop":1032.174,"duration":10.21}]},{"speakerName":"Sarah Harrington","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would say two things.","start":1032.174,"stop":1033.14,"duration":0.97},{"text":"First, in both cases what you want is a clear statement of an intent to waive the sovereign's immunity, either by the Federal Government or the State government.","start":1033.14,"stop":1040.011,"duration":6.87},{"text":"And also that it's important to keep in mind that in cases such as Franklin and Barnes, this Court was construing statutes that did not say anything about what remedies were appropriate, didn't mention remedies whatsoever.","start":1040.011,"stop":1051.136,"duration":11.13},{"text":"And so we don't rely so much on RLUIPA's use of the phrase \"appropriate relief\" as we do on the Spending Clause context.","start":1051.136,"stop":1058.39,"duration":7.25}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But those cases did not involve States, right?","start":1058.39,"stop":1061.61,"duration":3.22}]},{"speakerName":"Sarah Harrington","textObjs":[{"text":"Those cases did not involve States, that's true.","start":1061.61,"stop":1063.927,"duration":2.32},{"text":"But--","start":1063.927,"stop":1064.646,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"And I think that the -- the core question here is the State -- and Justice Alito just posed it: the State is being treated with less dignity than the Federal Government, because your position is that the Federal Government is shielded by its sovereign immunity, and you say the State is not.","start":1064.646,"stop":1091.546,"duration":26.9}]},{"speakerName":"Sarah Harrington","textObjs":[{"text":"--On the contrary, as to the dignity point, Your Honor, if -- the State voluntarily waives its immunity when it accepts Federal funds that clearly condition the acceptance of the funds on the waiver of its immunity.","start":1091.546,"stop":1103.252,"duration":11.71},{"text":"The State in this case doesn't contest that it has waived its sovereign immunity voluntarily to some universe of suits to enforce RLUIPA--","start":1103.252,"stop":1110.839,"duration":7.59}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"But we are talking about general principles of interpretation and the proposition that we are suggesting is that the State surely should be entitled to the same dignity, the same protection against suits as the Federal Government, and you suggest just the opposite.","start":1110.839,"stop":1127.3,"duration":16.46}]},{"speakerName":"Sarah Harrington","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, Your Honor.","start":1127.3,"stop":1127.917,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"And it seems to me that's contrary to standard principles of the Federal -- of protecting the Federal balance.","start":1127.917,"stop":1135.104,"duration":7.19}]},{"speakerName":"Sarah Harrington","textObjs":[{"text":"If you were construing a State statute that voluntarily waived its own immunity, then you might -- we might say the use of appropriate relief in that statute should be construed the same as the use of appropriate relief in RFRA.","start":1135.104,"stop":1145.662,"duration":10.56},{"text":"But in this case you are not talking about a State's waiver of its immunity through its -- through statutory language.","start":1145.662,"stop":1150.381,"duration":4.72},{"text":"The Court said in College Savings Bank that when a -- when a State takes Federal funds that are conditioned on a waiver of immunity, it is the act of accepting the funds that is the waiver and it waives its immunity to suits to the extent that it has noticed that it is doing so.","start":1150.381,"stop":1164.291,"duration":13.91}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"But it's -- but it's only because they accept the funds at all that the Spending -- that the Spending Clause is even operative.","start":1164.291,"stop":1170.694,"duration":6.4}]},{"speakerName":"Sarah Harrington","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1170.694,"stop":1171.61,"duration":0.92},{"text":"But again, it's -- it's the act of accepting the funds that are clearly conditioned that constitutes the waiver.","start":1171.61,"stop":1176.681,"duration":5.07},{"text":"So that the waiver--","start":1176.681,"stop":1177.664,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But the waiver -- I mean, on the State side they can say it says \"appropriate relief\".","start":1177.664,"stop":1182.133,"duration":4.47},{"text":"All right; we accept that we are going to be vulnerable to an injunction suit.","start":1182.133,"stop":1189.072,"duration":6.94},{"text":"But we're the State and it's our treasury, and it is not appropriate relief.","start":1189.072,"stop":1195.475,"duration":6.4},{"text":"We didn't waive it.","start":1195.475,"stop":1196.925,"duration":1.45},{"text":"It's not -- doesn't say in the Spending Clause legislation that we open up our treasury.","start":1196.925,"stop":1206.117,"duration":9.19}]},{"speakerName":"Sarah Harrington","textObjs":[{"text":"--But there is no basis in either the Eleventh Amendment or the statutory provisions in RLUIPA for distinguishing relief of an injunctive nature from relief in damages against the State.","start":1206.117,"stop":1216.056,"duration":9.94},{"text":"The Eleventh Amendment talks about suits in law and in equity, and there is nothing in RLUIPA that would give the States notice that they are waiving their immunity to suits for injunctive relief, but not give them notice that they are waiving their immunity to suits for money damages.","start":1216.056,"stop":1228.547,"duration":12.49},{"text":"This Court--","start":1228.547,"stop":1229.397,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"The word \"appropriate\" -- the word \"appropriate\" would -- would suggest that to me.","start":1229.397,"stop":1233.682,"duration":4.29},{"text":"If -- if I'm a State attorney general, and I -- I know that the rule is sovereign immunity and -- and especially with regard to raids on the State treasury, I think it would be at least plausible that I would -- I would read \"appropriate relief\" not to include monetary relief.","start":1233.682,"stop":1254.345,"duration":20.66},{"text":"And we have said -- the language from our cases -- Lane says a waiver of sovereign immunity must be unequivocally expressed in the statutory text and will be strictly construed in terms of its scope in favor of the sovereign.","start":1254.345,"stop":1270.771,"duration":16.43},{"text":"That's -- that's a high test.","start":1270.771,"stop":1273.14,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Sarah Harrington","textObjs":[{"text":"--But even--","start":1273.14,"stop":1273.99,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- and although I might sit down and come out with a conclusion after intensive study that yes, maybe the best reading of this statute is that it allows money damages, I find it hard to say that it is unequivocally expressed in the statutory text.","start":1273.99,"stop":1291.535,"duration":17.55}]},{"speakerName":"Sarah Harrington","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, two things if I could, Your Honor.","start":1291.535,"stop":1292.971,"duration":1.44},{"text":"In Lane v. Pena, the question before the Court was it wasn't -- it was outside the Spending Clause context, because the question was whether section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act applied to the Federal Government, and when the Federal Government applies, even in the Spending Clause context, conditions on itself there is no contract-like relationship.","start":1292.971,"stop":1310.163,"duration":17.19},{"text":"But the second thing this Court said in Barnes--","start":1310.163,"stop":1313.032,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- you deny that it has to be unequivocal?","start":1313.032,"stop":1315.484,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Sarah Harrington","textObjs":[{"text":"--It has to be unequivocal, but -- but the context in which you are construing whether -- whether the sovereign is expressing its intent to waive its immunity is different when you are talking about the Federal Government applying obligations on itself than when you are talking about the Federal Government offering money to a State in -- in exchange for its agreeing to comply with--","start":1315.484,"stop":1335.231,"duration":19.75}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"But that has nothing to do with whether the language is clear or not to constitute a waiver.","start":1335.231,"stop":1339.582,"duration":4.35},{"text":"There is no principle of law that you are articulating that says it -- it has to be -- this is not clear enough for the Federal Government, but it is clear enough for the State.","start":1339.582,"stop":1351.057,"duration":11.47},{"text":"\"Appropriate relief\" either has a meaning or it doesn't.","start":1351.057,"stop":1353.942,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"Sarah Harrington","textObjs":[{"text":"--Right.","start":1353.942,"stop":1354.459,"duration":0.52},{"text":"And again, we are not relying so much on the use of the phrase \"appropriate relief\" in the statute.","start":1354.459,"stop":1358.496,"duration":4.04},{"text":"What that -- the work that does is it affirms that the background presumption of the Bell v. Hood cases applies to proper defendants under RLUIPA, which include State governments.","start":1358.496,"stop":1367.952,"duration":9.46},{"text":"But as this Court said in Barnes, when a -- when a recipient of Federal funds takes the funds, it is on notice that it is going to be subject not only to the remedies explicitly provided in the text of the relevant legislation, but also to remedies that are traditionally available in suits for breach of contract, and those include compensatory damages and injunctive relief.","start":1367.952,"stop":1386.563,"duration":18.61},{"text":"Now the State would have this Court turn that presumption, in terms of traditional contract rules, on its head by saying that this -- that this Court should hold that the State presumptively waived its immunity to suits for injunctive relief but not for damages.","start":1386.563,"stop":1400.823,"duration":14.26}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"What do you say about -- I think I read in one of these briefs that what I think is the most relevant similar statute, RFRA, has been held not to encompass the same word -- not to encompass the monetary relief, and also there was some legislative history where people testified and told Congress at the time that the word \"appropriate\" won't encompass monetary relief.","start":1400.823,"stop":1425.371,"duration":24.55},{"text":"Am I remembering that correctly?","start":1425.371,"stop":1427.273,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"Sarah Harrington","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would give you the same answer I just gave, which is that we are not pointing so much to the use of the -- using the phrase \"appropriate relief\" in the statute as we are to the Spending Clause context.","start":1427.273,"stop":1435.413,"duration":8.14},{"text":"And this Court has held that when there is these conditions placed on Federal funds, the recipient of the funds understands when it takes the money that when it intentionally violates the conditions to which it has agreed it will be subject to suit for money damages.","start":1435.413,"stop":1448.487,"duration":13.07}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But then you're bracketing the State with counties and municipalities.","start":1448.487,"stop":1452.791,"duration":4.3},{"text":"It really comes down to a question -- who decides whether the state fisc is touched.","start":1452.791,"stop":1462.146,"duration":9.36},{"text":"And why isn't it most appropriate for this Court to say, Congress can call it either way, but our rule is, Congress, if you want to reach the State treasury, you have to say so explicitly.","start":1462.146,"stop":1478.34,"duration":16.19},{"text":"And then there is no doubt when the State enters a contract that it's going to be subject to money damages as well as injunctive relief.","start":1478.34,"stop":1487.714,"duration":9.37}]},{"speakerName":"Sarah Harrington","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, this Court has consistently applied a clear notice requirement to conditions that Congress places on Federal funds.","start":1487.714,"stop":1493.35,"duration":5.64},{"text":"That clear notice requirement arose out of cases like Pennhurst and South Dakota v. Dole, in which there were State recipients of Federal funds.","start":1493.35,"stop":1500.271,"duration":6.92},{"text":"And the Court said that the validity of Congress's constitutional action in exercising its Spending Clause authority depends on it giving the recipients of the funds clear notice of the conditions that they are agreeing to because of the contract-like nature of Spending Clause legislation.","start":1500.271,"stop":1517.733,"duration":17.46},{"text":"Now, that same rule was applied in Franklin and Gebser and Davis and Dole, even though the defendants in those cases were not sovereigns.","start":1517.733,"stop":1524.821,"duration":7.09},{"text":"It's still the same notice requirement and there is no reason to think that a county government would be able to understand, would be on notice that it would be subject to compensatory damages suits, and a State government would not.","start":1524.821,"stop":1535.612,"duration":10.79},{"text":"To be sure, the State government has more to give up.","start":1535.612,"stop":1537.731,"duration":2.12},{"text":"It might be a harder choice for the State about whether to take the money or not.","start":1537.731,"stop":1541.365,"duration":3.63},{"text":"But the choice is the State's, and when it says yes, I'm going to take this money, it agrees to the conditions that are attached to the money.","start":1541.365,"stop":1547.252,"duration":5.89}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":1547.252,"stop":1548.819,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Sarah Harrington","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":1548.819,"stop":1549.319,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Ho.","start":1549.319,"stop":1553.573,"duration":4.25}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court: the phrase \"appropriate relief\" is a textbook example of ambiguity, not unmistakable clarity.","start":1553.573,"stop":1564.095,"duration":10.52},{"text":"And that should end the inquiry.","start":1564.095,"stop":1566.297,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"If it is, why is injunctive relief included at all?","start":1566.297,"stop":1570.416,"duration":4.12},{"text":"Meaning, what you seem to be saying to me is that no relief should be appropriate, because no relief is clear whether it's injunctive relief or damages?","start":1570.416,"stop":1580.473,"duration":10.06}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"We agree with the U.S.'s reading of RFRA.","start":1580.473,"stop":1584.925,"duration":4.45},{"text":"The same should attach here.","start":1584.925,"stop":1586.041,"duration":1.12},{"text":"There is an express cause of action.","start":1586.041,"stop":1587.707,"duration":1.67},{"text":"So that cause of action has to do something and we are applying to that express cause of action the narrowest reading, which is--","start":1587.707,"stop":1595.73,"duration":8.02}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Some would say that injunctive relief attaches more to the public FISC then compensatory relief.","start":1595.73,"stop":1604.003,"duration":8.27},{"text":"Because future conduct or change of conduct can have an enormous intrusion on the public FISC, so why do we draw the line between saying one is more intrusive than the other?","start":1604.003,"stop":1617.643,"duration":13.64}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"--Two answers, Your Honor.","start":1617.643,"stop":1619.345,"duration":1.7},{"text":"The traditional line drawing that you see in sovereign immunity is injunctive relief.","start":1619.345,"stop":1623.797,"duration":4.45},{"text":"Any prospective relief is less intrusive on sovereign immunity than any form of retrospective relief, damages and that sort of thing.","start":1623.797,"stop":1633.486,"duration":9.69},{"text":"But especially true in this context, because when you talk about the Spending Clause, we can walk away from injunctive relief, from an injunction at any time.","start":1633.486,"stop":1641.259,"duration":7.77},{"text":"We can simply stop receiving the funds and stop accepting the funds and the injunction evaporates, but we can't walk away from a damage remedy.","start":1641.259,"stop":1649.03,"duration":7.77},{"text":"So we are construing the express cause of action in RLUIPA, like in RFRA, to do the judicial minimum.","start":1649.03,"stop":1655.617,"duration":6.59},{"text":"Which is that judicial relief which requires states to do what we are already required to do, which is to comply with the substantial burden mandatory under RLUIPA.","start":1655.617,"stop":1666.742,"duration":11.13},{"text":"So the fact that appropriate relief is essentially inherently ambiguous should end the analysis, because after all, the Court is required unmistakably clear text and rejected merely permissible inferences for two reasons, to ensure both careful, robust deliberation by Congress before disturbing the federal state balance of power, as well as to ensure clear notice.","start":1666.742,"stop":1692.44,"duration":25.7}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"I was looking at the cases the best I can at the moment.","start":1692.44,"stop":1695.492,"duration":3.05},{"text":"I think you might say that there are a lot of cases which interpret the word \"appropriate relief\" to include monetary relief.","start":1695.492,"stop":1703.915,"duration":8.42},{"text":"And then there is some that don't.","start":1703.915,"stop":1705.95,"duration":2.04},{"text":"And to get a rule out of them, you would have to say, well, they are looking to context.","start":1705.95,"stop":1710.485,"duration":4.53},{"text":"And in context it sometimes is clear, sometimes occasionally not.","start":1710.485,"stop":1714.889,"duration":4.4},{"text":"But here, isn't this and maybe this was asked, but I want your answer.","start":1714.889,"stop":1720.377,"duration":5.49},{"text":"The context here, the words appropriate relief, govern both the prison situation and the land use situation, don't they?","start":1720.377,"stop":1729.315,"duration":8.94},{"text":"You are given an action when the government through a general land use regulation infringes somebody's right to build, for example.","start":1729.315,"stop":1740.021,"duration":10.71},{"text":"Now, wouldn't that kind of interference with the use of property quite often and normally require some kind of monetary compensation?","start":1740.021,"stop":1749.979,"duration":9.96},{"text":"This isn't just the odd thing in a prison, where it's talking about it might be called building a religious building or building some kind of parking, all kinds of things that have monetary compensation.","start":1749.979,"stop":1767.54,"duration":17.56},{"text":"Do you see my question?","start":1767.54,"stop":1768.724,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"I think I do, Your Honor.","start":1768.724,"stop":1770.059,"duration":1.34},{"text":"First of all, we certainly agree that your premise, which is that context matters, the Court has said specifically appropriate relief can enlarge or contract, it could be mean monetary or it could mean not monetary, so it does depend on context.","start":1770.059,"stop":1781.165,"duration":11.11},{"text":"I confess that your land use question is interesting, we are obviously focused on section 3.","start":1781.165,"stop":1787.319,"duration":6.15}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"I know, but isn't it the same word that governs both?","start":1787.319,"stop":1790.069,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"It is the same word.","start":1790.069,"stop":1791.604,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"If it's the same word that governs both and if land cases very often involve claims for money, I would think that would cut against you.","start":1791.604,"stop":1800.543,"duration":8.94},{"text":"But that's why I ask.","start":1800.543,"stop":1803.512,"duration":2.97},{"text":"I want to get your response.","start":1803.512,"stop":1804.612,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we are still looking for express language in the text.","start":1804.612,"stop":1808.147,"duration":3.53}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"But there are loads of cases that have nothing more than appropriate relief and in those cases context makes it clear.","start":1808.147,"stop":1815.735,"duration":7.59},{"text":"The only one really I thought strongly -- your strongest case seems to me to be RFRA.","start":1815.735,"stop":1823.989,"duration":8.25}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"RFRA certainly is the direct context from which the words appropriate relief in this statute are drawn.","start":1823.989,"stop":1830.245,"duration":6.26},{"text":"And RFRA, of course, is land use, it's prisons, it's anything, RFRA applies to the federal government or any activity under the sun.","start":1830.245,"stop":1830.245,"duration":0}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Uh-huh.","start":1830.245,"stop":1836.983,"duration":6.74}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"So for that reason alone, I think we might resist the notion that the specific uses of appropriate relief in RLUIPA would somehow provide any sort of change or certainly any expectation that we would have or that Congress would have, for that matter, that the words appropriate relief would take on a new meaning just because it's land use.","start":1836.983,"stop":1854.176,"duration":17.19}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean, so often, what I'm thinking of, a church wands to build, and they can't because of a land restriction.","start":1854.176,"stop":1862.281,"duration":8.11},{"text":"And it turns out that that land restriction violates this statute.","start":1862.281,"stop":1866.502,"duration":4.22},{"text":"And in the meantime they have had to rent buildings, they have had to maybe build somewhere else and they have had to do all kinds of things that cost money.","start":1866.502,"stop":1874.156,"duration":7.65},{"text":"And that's why I would think in that context money would be a natural thing.","start":1874.156,"stop":1878.726,"duration":4.57}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not sure though--","start":1878.726,"stop":1880.11,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"To fulfill appropriateness.","start":1880.11,"stop":1881.678,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"--I'm actually not sure that that would be true even in that context.","start":1881.678,"stop":1884.797,"duration":3.12},{"text":"Certainly anybody might want money, but when it comes to what Congress has indicated and what states would expect, I would imagine that the federal government's biggest interest is in making sure that states and other recipients use the money for what it's supposed to be for, comply with the substantial burden mandate.","start":1884.797,"stop":1902.758,"duration":17.96},{"text":"And a local government is not doing so with regard to a church, then they should be enjoined so that they would be required to comply with it.","start":1902.758,"stop":1911.495,"duration":8.74},{"text":"If anything, damages might exacerbate the problem just in the sense that we are now taking federal money and applying damages to it.","start":1911.495,"stop":1918.434,"duration":6.94}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought a local government would be subject to damages.","start":1918.434,"stop":1921.886,"duration":3.45},{"text":"We are talking about the state.","start":1921.886,"stop":1923.672,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"We are talking about the state, Your Honor.","start":1923.672,"stop":1925.622,"duration":1.95},{"text":"To be clear, we do not actually concede that damages would even be available against a local government.","start":1925.622,"stop":1932.176,"duration":6.55},{"text":"Our point here is that simply it doesn't matter for us, because we obviously are treated very differently from local governments.","start":1932.176,"stop":1938.746,"duration":6.57},{"text":"I think they have, both the Petitioner and U.S. have indicated that the statute should treat state and locals the same way.","start":1938.746,"stop":1945.817,"duration":7.07},{"text":"The problem with that is the Constitution obviously treats states and locals very differently.","start":1945.817,"stop":1951.019,"duration":5.2},{"text":"The Constitution treats the state and federal government in the same way, in that both enjoy sovereign immunity and included in that are the principles of sovereign immunity, the need for specific waiver, not just a clear waiver, but specific as to the scope of the waiver, and specific as to the remedies.","start":1951.019,"stop":1969.23,"duration":18.21}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So now we have three distinctions.","start":1969.23,"stop":1971.848,"duration":2.62},{"text":"With respect to land use discrimination, the Rehab Act would presumably apply.","start":1971.848,"stop":1977.919,"duration":6.07},{"text":"So the Rehab Act says compensatory damages are permissible for that kind of discriminatory claim, so now we have compensatory damages for that.","start":1977.919,"stop":1991.144,"duration":13.22},{"text":"We have, potentially, compensatory damages for local governments, but not for State or Federal level.","start":1991.144,"stop":1997.48,"duration":6.34},{"text":"We are chopping up the statute at each stage, correct?","start":1997.48,"stop":2003.201,"duration":5.72},{"text":"We are treating different defendants differently and different claims differently with respect to the relief that's permissible?","start":2003.201,"stop":2011.807,"duration":8.61}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"That would not be our submission, Your Honor.","start":2011.807,"stop":2013.557,"duration":1.75},{"text":"If we are talking about the 2000d(7) language, all that 2000(d)(7) says if you are a provision prohibiting discrimination, then you get the same remedies against a State that you would get against any other nonsovereign defendant.","start":2013.557,"stop":2030.019,"duration":16.46},{"text":"And if we were representing the City of Austin, we actually would argue -- we think we have good arguments -- that damages would not be available even against the City of Austin.","start":2030.019,"stop":2038.023,"duration":8},{"text":"Our point here is simply that--","start":2038.023,"stop":2039.706,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Could you explain why?","start":2039.706,"stop":2041.14,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"--Sure.","start":2041.14,"stop":2041.707,"duration":0.57},{"text":"I think if I were the City of Austin, I would make three arguments.","start":2041.707,"stop":2044.009,"duration":2.3},{"text":"One, the words \"appropriate relief\" are in the statute.","start":2044.009,"stop":2047.627,"duration":3.62},{"text":"I think they -- the other one wants to read this as surplusage.","start":2047.627,"stop":2050.329,"duration":2.7},{"text":"We would think that the words v. Gibson, noting that the words \"appropriate relief\" seemed to indicate equitable discretion, or discretion, and therefore equitable relief.","start":2050.329,"stop":2067.273,"duration":16.94},{"text":"In addition, we will note that the words (4)(A)--","start":2067.273,"stop":2071.077,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"But equity permits money as well.","start":2071.077,"stop":2072.693,"duration":1.62},{"text":"Equity permits money as well.","start":2072.693,"stop":2075.362,"duration":2.67}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"--In some limited formats, but it wouldn't be compensatory damages in the sense that we are talking about in this case.","start":2075.362,"stop":2081.116,"duration":5.75},{"text":"An additional indication would be the fact that the words \"appropriate relief\" aren't just attached to the claim.","start":2081.116,"stop":2087.419,"duration":6.3},{"text":"It's attached to both claim or defense.","start":2087.419,"stop":2090.204,"duration":2.79},{"text":"And of course it makes no sense to say that you can get money damages by asserting RLUIPA as a defense.","start":2090.204,"stop":2096.358,"duration":6.15},{"text":"So for all those reasons, the City of Austin might actually have a good case that damages aren't available even against them.","start":2096.358,"stop":2102.846,"duration":6.49},{"text":"Of course, it doesn't matter for our case, because the whole point is if the City of Austin were to lose due to Barnes and Franklin, what we know for sure here is that Barnes and Franklin have nothing, nothing whatsoever, to do with the States.","start":2102.846,"stop":2114.737,"duration":11.89},{"text":"If I may, I would like to spend a little bit of time on that issue.","start":2114.737,"stop":2117.689,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Before you do that, Barnes and Franklin were cases involving implied rights of action; isn't that right?","start":2117.689,"stop":2122.842,"duration":5.15}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2122.842,"stop":2126.544,"duration":3.7},{"text":"With the 2000d(7) backdrop, but yes, Your Honor.","start":2126.544,"stop":2129.377,"duration":2.83}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":2129.377,"stop":2131.929,"duration":2.55}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"And I'm -- this one question may be covered, but can you give me any examples where States have turned down money under the Spending Clause, say we don't want it, the restrictions are too great?","start":2131.929,"stop":2146.856,"duration":14.93},{"text":"Does this happen all the time, or ever?","start":2146.856,"stop":2149.724,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"Where States turn down money?","start":2149.724,"stop":2151.01,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Where States tell the Federal Government: No, thank you, we don't want the money.","start":2151.01,"stop":2153.778,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"It's starting to happen in Texas.","start":2153.778,"stop":2155.878,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Under programs like this?","start":2155.878,"stop":2160.866,"duration":4.99}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't -- I can't think of a situation where Texas has turned down RLUIPA Federal prison money.","start":2160.866,"stop":2167.002,"duration":6.14},{"text":"But there--","start":2167.002,"stop":2167.954,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean other States -- they say, oh, the liabilities are just too great, we don't want it?","start":2167.954,"stop":2172.256,"duration":4.3}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"--I'm not aware of any State in the country that has turned down Federal prison funds.","start":2172.256,"stop":2176.874,"duration":4.62},{"text":"Of course, if damages were somehow inflicted, if Congress changed the law, perhaps States would start to recalibrate that decision.","start":2176.874,"stop":2185.48,"duration":8.61},{"text":"Their core argument is that we should just extend Franklin and Barnes to States.","start":2185.48,"stop":2192.218,"duration":6.74},{"text":"The fatal flaw with that argument is that the very principle on which Franklin and Barnes apply -- are premised, that principle does not apply to sovereigns.","start":2192.218,"stop":2202.608,"duration":10.39},{"text":"When Congress passes a cause of action and is silent or ambiguous with respect to the remedies, there is a traditional presumption that we apply.","start":2202.608,"stop":2213.999,"duration":11.39},{"text":"Non-sovereigns now expect to be subject to any possible remedy under the sun.","start":2213.999,"stop":2220.753,"duration":6.75},{"text":"Precisely the opposite rule applies to sovereigns.","start":2220.753,"stop":2225.189,"duration":4.44},{"text":"We know that for sure as a matter of precedent in Lane, which rejected Franklin as applied to a sovereign.","start":2225.189,"stop":2230.943,"duration":5.75},{"text":"We also know this as a more fundamental basic principle of sovereign immunity, because when it comes to sovereigns, we have to have not only a clear waiver, but also a waiver that is specific to the remedy that is being sought.","start":2230.943,"stop":2243.852,"duration":12.91},{"text":"These two rules can't be reconciled.","start":2243.852,"stop":2245.652,"duration":1.8},{"text":"You either can apply the traditional presumption of all remedies, or you apply the other rule that sovereigns benefit from.","start":2245.652,"stop":2252.708,"duration":7.06},{"text":"Petitioner claims that maybe a special rule should apply that is unique to the Spending Clause, that maybe that's a way to get around the sovereign immunity problem, but we submit that fundamentally misreads Franklin and Barnes, because what's doing the work in Franklin and Barnes isn't the Spending Clause.","start":2252.708,"stop":2272.27,"duration":19.56},{"text":"It's actually quite the opposite.","start":2272.27,"stop":2273.52,"duration":1.25},{"text":"The Spending Clause is cutting back against the traditional presumption.","start":2273.52,"stop":2277.405,"duration":3.89},{"text":"In Franklin -- I will take each case in turn.","start":2277.405,"stop":2279.523,"duration":2.12},{"text":"In Franklin, you see pages and pages of analysis in section 2 of the opinion, where there is exhaustive research about Bell v. Hood and the traditional presumptions that the Court has applied for decades under any thought of Federal power.","start":2279.523,"stop":2293.683,"duration":14.16},{"text":"The Spending Clause makes an appearance in Franklin only at the very end in section 4, invoked by the defense as a potential reason not to apply the traditional presumption.","start":2293.683,"stop":2304.205,"duration":10.52},{"text":"The court, you know, gets past that on the grounds that the traditional presumption is so strong that it does provide the clarity for non-sovereigns.","start":2304.205,"stop":2311.525,"duration":7.32},{"text":"It doesn't indisputably apply to non-sovereigns; why not apply it under the Spending Clause as well?","start":2311.525,"stop":2316.179,"duration":4.65},{"text":"The point, though, is it's not the Spending Clause that does the work.","start":2316.179,"stop":2320.215,"duration":4.04},{"text":"It is -- it is the traditional presumption.","start":2320.215,"stop":2323.166,"duration":2.95},{"text":"That has even more dramatic force in Barnes v. Gorman.","start":2323.166,"stop":2326.368,"duration":3.2},{"text":"Mr. Gorman would have had a $1.2 million punitive damage award that he would have been entitled to, except for the fact that this was a Spending Clause case, and that's precisely why he lost that punitive damage award.","start":2326.368,"stop":2340.776,"duration":14.41},{"text":"So put simply, yes, it could be that under Barnes and Franklin, remedies would be clear enough in that one context.","start":2340.776,"stop":2351.067,"duration":10.29},{"text":"The problem is it's not clear enough in this context, because sovereigns present a completely different constitutional context.","start":2351.067,"stop":2358.154,"duration":7.09},{"text":"I want to address very quickly Justice Sotomayor's question about Ex parte Young.","start":2358.154,"stop":2363.106,"duration":4.95},{"text":"I think you were exactly right that Ex parte -- that our reading isn't in any way redundant with Ex parte Young, but I want to note an additional reason why we are not redundant.","start":2363.106,"stop":2372.211,"duration":9.1},{"text":"We need to confirm, Congress needed to confirm, that there was in fact a privately enforceable right, and that's why our reading in no way renders the Ex parte Young concept redundant.","start":2372.211,"stop":2385.471,"duration":13.26}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"What do you do with the practical problem that's been brought up that if a State is sued, it can release the prisoner, it can transfer the prisoner, and then no relief is appropriate?","start":2385.471,"stop":2403.016,"duration":17.55},{"text":"That the only way that the State is going to take its obligation seriously is if it's exposed to compensatory damages?","start":2403.016,"stop":2414.49,"duration":11.47}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"If a prisoner is transferred, released, or the State simply changes its mind and gives up and provides the accommodation, in all those situations, the prisoner is no longer suffering from the complaint of condition.","start":2414.49,"stop":2428.231,"duration":13.74},{"text":"That's why this Court's mootness doctrines would apply.","start":2428.231,"stop":2431.35,"duration":3.12},{"text":"Put another way, mootness is really just another word for settlement, and we would think that settlement, the State essentially capitulating and saying: Our bad, we should have complied, we should have provided the accommodation, that actually vindicates the purpose of RLUIPA, and indeed, it avoids the need for costly litigation to do so.","start":2431.35,"stop":2449.996,"duration":18.65},{"text":"I want to mention briefly the U.S.--","start":2449.996,"stop":2452.865,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"What's the inducement to do it more quickly rather than to delay, to remedy the wrong faster rather than to delay?","start":2452.865,"stop":2461.035,"duration":8.17}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"--The reason to do it?","start":2461.035,"stop":2462.821,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Uh-huh.","start":2462.821,"stop":2463.504,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"Simply to avoid litigation.","start":2463.504,"stop":2465.173,"duration":1.67},{"text":"I mean, the way this works practically on the ground, prisons obviously have a lot to deal with, a lot of security concerns.","start":2465.173,"stop":2471.327,"duration":6.15},{"text":"They set general policies.","start":2471.327,"stop":2472.843,"duration":1.52},{"text":"They may not be aware that their policy might have an implication for a certain individual of a particular faith.","start":2472.843,"stop":2479.08,"duration":6.24},{"text":"If that's brought to their attention and--","start":2479.08,"stop":2481.563,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"That's an ideal world, that they'll respond, but there is an allegation that some prisons wait until the eve of the trial after onerous discovery on the plaintiff and after enormous harm to plaintiffs, physical and otherwise, before they capitulate.","start":2481.563,"stop":2499.058,"duration":17.49},{"text":"So what's the inducement?","start":2499.058,"stop":2500.493,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, the inducement is to--","start":2500.493,"stop":2503.028,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"To move faster.","start":2503.028,"stop":2504.262,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"--States are -- States are suffering the litigation costs as well.","start":2504.262,"stop":2507.464,"duration":3.2},{"text":"We are not in the business to litigate just because we want to.","start":2507.464,"stop":2509.947,"duration":2.48},{"text":"We have plenty of other suits to deal with.","start":2509.947,"stop":2511.38,"duration":1.43},{"text":"This very case, I think, is a good example.","start":2511.38,"stop":2513.065,"duration":1.68},{"text":"Once the prisoner -- once Mr. Sossamon agreed with respect to the salt restriction policy, we immediately abandoned that policy, before litigation was even filed.","start":2513.065,"stop":2522.255,"duration":9.19},{"text":"With respect to the U.S. cause of action provision, there was an argument that appropriate relief has to mean damages, because otherwise just take that declaratory or injunctive relief language and put it into the private cause of action.","start":2522.255,"stop":2536.847,"duration":14.59},{"text":"The reason that argument doesn't work is because these are two fundamentally different provisions.","start":2536.847,"stop":2541.732,"duration":4.88},{"text":"There is (4)(F) of RFRA, which is the U.S. cause of action, and there was (4)(A) of -- I'm sorry, of RLUIPA -- and there is (4)(A) of RLUIPA, which is not just a private cause of action, but also a defense.","start":2541.732,"stop":2553.274,"duration":11.54},{"text":"So again, if you can imagine sticking in the words (4)(A), it doesn't work.","start":2553.274,"stop":2560.111,"duration":6.84},{"text":"It doesn't make any sense, because what person asserting a defense would seek an injunctive relief?","start":2560.111,"stop":2565.582,"duration":5.47},{"text":"If you take what's--","start":2565.582,"stop":2567.132,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me ask -- get this information from you.","start":2567.132,"stop":2569.2,"duration":2.07},{"text":"As I understand it, there are some cases that find the words \"appropriate relief\" in a statute to include damages and there's some that don't.","start":2569.2,"stop":2580.841,"duration":11.64},{"text":"Let's look at the ones that don't.","start":2580.841,"stop":2582.391,"duration":1.55},{"text":"There is some where it's pretty hard to do it because it's in a heading called \"injunction\", and that's obvious.","start":2582.391,"stop":2589.363,"duration":6.97},{"text":"But there are only two statutes, really, where the courts have ever held in significant numbers that the word \"appropriate relief\" does not include money damages.","start":2589.363,"stop":2599.903,"duration":10.54},{"text":"One is the IDEA, the Disabilities Act, and the other is RFRA.","start":2599.903,"stop":2606.492,"duration":6.59},{"text":"Is there anything else that you've come across?","start":2606.492,"stop":2610.277,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"--Those are two great examples.","start":2610.277,"stop":2612.144,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but are there any others?","start":2612.144,"stop":2613.31,"duration":1.17},{"text":"I mean, I just want to get down on a piece of paper what I have to look at.","start":2613.31,"stop":2616.612,"duration":3.3}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"Sure.","start":2616.612,"stop":2616.996,"duration":0.38},{"text":"I think there are two -- two great examples.","start":2616.996,"stop":2618.631,"duration":1.63},{"text":"I would note--","start":2618.631,"stop":2619.181,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":2619.181,"stop":2619.698,"duration":0.52},{"text":"So you don't have any others, I'm judging from your hesitation.","start":2619.698,"stop":2621.75,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, no -- I would actually -- I would note there are two other cases--","start":2621.75,"stop":2624.035,"duration":2.28}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"What?","start":2624.035,"stop":2624.218,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"--that I would refer you to, and of course discussed in the briefs.","start":2624.218,"stop":2627.237,"duration":3.02},{"text":"West v. Gibson which talks about how the words appropriate relief, remedies in that context, by definition have no fixed meaning; they can't possibly have fixed meaning.","start":2627.237,"stop":2637.592,"duration":10.36},{"text":"So it has to enlarge or contract.","start":2637.592,"stop":2639.044,"duration":1.45},{"text":"And prior to 1991 -- prior to 1991 amendment at issue in that case -- the Court would unanimously agreed that appropriate relief would not have included money damages.","start":2639.044,"stop":2649.417,"duration":10.37},{"text":"Ruckelshaus provides similar guidance, in that I think the phrase was, there was no possible -- no comprehensible or principled meaning to the phrase \"appropriate\" as attached to a remedy.","start":2649.417,"stop":2661.375,"duration":11.96},{"text":"I will briefly touch on the 2000d-7 issue unless there are questions about that.","start":2661.375,"stop":2669.314,"duration":7.94},{"text":"Assuming the issue is even preserved for this Court's consideration, 2000d-7 doesn't allow relief, either.","start":2669.314,"stop":2676.05,"duration":6.74},{"text":"I think there are a lot of reasons why that would be so, but I think the simplest is simply to acknowledge the difference between section 2 of RLUIPA and section 3.","start":2676.05,"stop":2685.673,"duration":9.62},{"text":"Section 2 of RLUIPA is much like the four provisions expressly enumerated in 2000d-7, in that all of them have the word discrimination and more importantly turn on the concept of discrimination.","start":2685.673,"stop":2698.381,"duration":12.71},{"text":"A discrimination is an element of a cause of action under section 2, or under any of the four provisions enumerated.","start":2698.381,"stop":2705.07,"duration":6.69},{"text":"By contrast section 3 is not.","start":2705.07,"stop":2707.353,"duration":2.28},{"text":"You can have discrimination as -- as part of your fact background if you want but it will have nothing whatsoever to do with whether have you a valid section 3 claim or not.","start":2707.353,"stop":2716.276,"duration":8.92}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- you have already addressed this but I think it's their -- the position of your friend on the other side of the case is that with the Spending Clause you have a contract.","start":2716.276,"stop":2726.714,"duration":10.44},{"text":"The State has some extra protection, and therefore we need not be quite so strict in -- in construing waivers -- waivers of immunity, because you have the contract.","start":2726.714,"stop":2740.224,"duration":13.51},{"text":"Can you comment on that argument?","start":2740.224,"stop":2743.259,"duration":3.03},{"text":"And -- and you might want to say that the Spending Clause is potentially so sweeping that the State should have special protection and we should be particularly careful about the clear statement rule.","start":2743.259,"stop":2757.935,"duration":14.68},{"text":"Or do you think the clear statement rule applies with equal force whether it's a Spending Clause or a direct regulation under say, the Fourteenth Amendment?","start":2757.935,"stop":2766.708,"duration":8.77}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"I'll try to take each of those points in turn.","start":2766.708,"stop":2771.176,"duration":4.47},{"text":"We don't see anything in the law that suggests that sometimes there is a clear statement rule and sometimes there is a super-duper clear statement rule.","start":2771.176,"stop":2780.198,"duration":9.02},{"text":"I think there has been some suggestion -- or maybe there has not been any more; I'm not sure; I read the briefs the same way, I think the same way that the Justices did.","start":2780.198,"stop":2787.686,"duration":7.49},{"text":"But they seem not to be arguing that any more.","start":2787.686,"stop":2789.702,"duration":2.02},{"text":"So it should be the same standard.","start":2789.702,"stop":2792.654,"duration":2.95},{"text":"I -- I certainly acknowledge that when it comes to the Spending Clause as you wrote in your dissent in Davis v. Monroe, that the Spending Clause if anything does raise special constitutional considerations as a general matter, inasmuch as the Spending Clause could be used to impose Federal restrictions on States that they could never dream of under Article I otherwise.","start":2792.654,"stop":2813.483,"duration":20.83},{"text":"RLUIPA of course is a prime example of that.","start":2813.483,"stop":2816.333,"duration":2.85},{"text":"But at the end of the day, the Spending Clause is not doing any work with regard to providing an assumption or presumption of remedies.","start":2816.333,"stop":2826.124,"duration":9.79},{"text":"Again, it's exactly precisely the opposite.","start":2826.124,"stop":2828.843,"duration":2.72},{"text":"Franklin and Barnes both articulate that it's the traditional presumption that applies to any exercise of Federal power.","start":2828.843,"stop":2837.181,"duration":8.34},{"text":"That traditional presumption is what's doing the work.","start":2837.181,"stop":2839.581,"duration":2.4},{"text":"The Spending Clause if anything is a cut back.","start":2839.581,"stop":2841.633,"duration":2.05},{"text":"So the notion that just invoking the Spending Clause suddenly puts States on this fabulously clear notice, I think just does not work.","start":2841.633,"stop":2849.656,"duration":8.02},{"text":"If there are no further questions, Your Honor?","start":2849.656,"stop":2852.358,"duration":2.7}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Ho.","start":2852.358,"stop":2853.524,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"James C. Ho","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":2853.524,"stop":2853.908,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Russell, you have four minutes remaining.","start":2853.908,"stop":2861.995,"duration":8.09}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":2861.995,"stop":2862.764,"duration":0.77},{"text":"Nearly every argument the state made here today could have been made by the local governments in Barnes.","start":2862.764,"stop":2869.084,"duration":6.32},{"text":"Ranging from the complaint that the language like appropriate relief is too unclear, to the assertion that they were not on notice, that by accepting federal funds they were subjecting themselves to suits.","start":2869.084,"stop":2881.225,"duration":12.14},{"text":"And that's because the local government, like any other state, had the same right to the same clear statement rule.","start":2881.225,"stop":2886.593,"duration":5.37},{"text":"Unless this Court is, in fact, going to create a proliferation or hierarchy of clear statement rules, the Pennhurst rule that applies in the Spending Clause context of local governments applies in exactly the same way to a state government under the Eleventh Amendment and Barnes' Court construed the express private right of action under section 504, which incorporated by reference the remedies available under Title XI, which this Court construed to authorize appropriate relief.","start":2886.593,"stop":2913.91,"duration":27.32},{"text":"Exactly the same remedy that RLUIPA authorizes.","start":2913.91,"stop":2918.195,"duration":4.29},{"text":"And so the state for the first time today has suggested that the city of Austin is not bound by Barnes.","start":2918.195,"stop":2924.432,"duration":6.24},{"text":"I don't see how they can reach that conclusion.","start":2924.432,"stop":2927.198,"duration":2.77},{"text":"Barnes quite clearly says that the local government is subject to -- and is on notice that it has clear, there is a clear statement in every Spending Clause statute that they are subject to a damages remedy so long as they accept the funds because of the contractual nature of the obligation.","start":2927.198,"stop":2942.826,"duration":15.63},{"text":"That applies.","start":2942.826,"stop":2943.926,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Was that contested in Barnes?","start":2943.926,"stop":2946.692,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"Which part, I'm sorry.","start":2946.692,"stop":2948.561,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Was the liability for compensatory damages contested in Barnes?","start":2948.561,"stop":2955.032,"duration":6.47}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2955.032,"stop":2955.365,"duration":0.33},{"text":"The question in Barnes is punitive.","start":2955.365,"stop":2956.715,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Just punitive.","start":2956.715,"stop":2957.598,"duration":0.88},{"text":"And there is a lot of discussion, the assumption that they were liable for compensatory, but it really wasn't litigated, was it?","start":2957.598,"stop":2965.304,"duration":7.71}]},{"speakerName":"Kevin K. Russell","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the legal principle this Court adopted to resolve that issue was one that, I take it, was not just a principle for that case, but that in general, funding recipients are on notice that they are subject to contract remedies and unless this Court is going to back away from that as a general matter, unless the Court is going to say that Pennhurst applies differently in the Spending Clause context than it does in the sovereign immunity context, I don't see how you can come to a different result in this case.","start":2965.304,"stop":2993.454,"duration":28.15},{"text":"Justice Breyer, with respect to RFRA, as far as I know, there is only one court of appeals case that says the United States is not subject to suits and that was decided six years after RLUIPA was enacted.","start":2993.454,"stop":3003.91,"duration":10.46},{"text":"With respect to the IDEA, there are a handful of lower courts decisions that say damages are unavailable.","start":3003.91,"stop":3008.797,"duration":4.89},{"text":"Those -- they give reasons that are specific to the IDEA and the fact that that remedial provision is part of the due process hearing process there.","start":3008.797,"stop":3016.05,"duration":7.25},{"text":"In general, damages are the quintessential appropriate relief for violations of civil rights, and there is no reason to think that Congress was creating in RLUIPA a second class civil right that wasn't deserving of a remedy that Congress has provided even against states in every other context.","start":3016.05,"stop":3033.429,"duration":17.38},{"text":"With respect to the state's belief that the Eleventh Amendment somehow prefers injunctions over damages remedies, as counsel for the United States pointed out, the Eleventh Amendment is no basis for that.","start":3033.429,"stop":3045.403,"duration":11.97},{"text":"It treats injunctions and damages as equally offensive to state sovereignty, and in fact, particularly in RLUIPA, where damages are often capped significantly by the PLRA, the concern really ought to be on the states by injunctive relief, which will frequently have a much more significant effect on the public FISC than a small damages award.","start":3045.403,"stop":3064.816,"duration":19.41},{"text":"And finally with the state's argument that the words appropriate relief are too inherently ambiguous to meet any clear statement.","start":3064.816,"stop":3071.72,"duration":6.9},{"text":"Well, this Court rejected that kind of argument in West where it construed appropriate remedy to encompass a damages remedy by engaging an ordinary statutory interpretation, which is entirely appropriate in this context.","start":3071.72,"stop":3085.48,"duration":13.76},{"text":"This Court has repeatedly in cases like Ruckelshaus, for example, like Richlin, relied on how statutes apply with respect to private parties to give meaning to the otherwise ambiguous word \"appropriate\" in the federal statute waiving the federal government's sovereign immunity.","start":3085.48,"stop":3102.155,"duration":16.68},{"text":"Thank you.","start":3102.155,"stop":3105.107,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":3105.107,"stop":3106.041,"duration":0.93},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":3106.041,"stop":3106.943,"duration":0.9}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Roberts Court","arguedOn":"Nov 2, 2010","petitioner":"Harvey Leroy Sossamon, III","respondent":"Texas, et al.","docket":"08-1438","citation":"563 US 277 (2011)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/563/277","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit","grantedOn":"May 24, 2010","decidedOn":"Apr 20, 2011"}